What makes a song popular?¶

Most people listen to music in some form. It can range from hearing a catchy tune while at a grocery store, to having a devoted playlist for every emotion possibly felt throughout your day. But what makes a song widely enjoyable to a larger audience of people? What exactly makes a song popular? Imagine you are an artist trying to make the next biggest hit, and the goal is for your next song to make it to the Billboard End of the Year list. This exploratory data analysis will attempt to answer for what makes a song popular, and provide some insights for the hypothetical artist on the qualities of a popular song so they are better equipt to make the next best hit.

Using the search feature in the spotify api can return a lot of information about a given track, such as countries where it is available, all associated artists and links to their profile on spotify, popularity ranking, etc. Because of this we will now use the spotify search to get trackids and artistids. We can use the artist id to get the genre,and the track id to get features present within the actual song, such as "danceability" and "energy". Since we are searching by keyword, this can make the search results prone to errors, especially in a larger dataset like this (i.e. getting a live, acoustic, remix version of the original song we are searching for).

We cannot completely filter out remixes, as sometimes the remixes are what is more popular (i.e. Finesse Remix Bruno Mars ft. Cardi B). Therefore we will have a marker denoting whether the song is a remix for manual inspection. We will also search songs that have words such as 'Instrumental', 'Live', and 'Acoustic'. This won't completely filter out false search results, so in addition we will have a low popularity marker if the track popularity score is less than 40. A lower popularity score would increase the likelihood for a false search result, as all of the songs we are searching should in theory would have a higher popularity score.

Finally we will parse the artist by only focusing on the main artist (if there is a feature/other people in the track)

In [ ]:
def parse_artist(content):
    for split_token in [" & ", " \\ ", " feat ", " featuring ", " and "]:
        content = content.partition(split_token)[0]
    return content

Through this we can minimize the false results we will get when searching. We have empty lists which we will aggregate with values for each call to the Spotify API

Now we use the spotify api to search

In [ ]:
for row in df.iterrows():
    search = "%20track:" +row[1][0].replace("\"", "") + "%20artists:" + parse_artist(row[1][1]) #search term
    results = spotify.search(q=search,type='track', limit=2) #api call
    
    items = results['tracks']['items']
    if len(items) > 0:
        name = items[0]['name']
        #print(name)
        track_ids.append(items[0]['id'])
        artist_ids.append(items[0]['artists'][0]['id'])
        amt_features.append(len(items[0]['artists']) - 1)
        
        if "remix" in name.lower():
            remix.append(name)
        else:
            remix.append(np.nan)    
        
        if items[0]['popularity'] < 40:
            low_pop.append(name + ": " + str(items[0]['popularity']))
        else:
            low_pop.append(np.nan)
        
        if "instrumental" in name.lower() or "acoustic" in name.lower() or ("live" in name.lower() and "live" not in row[1][0].lower()):
            check.append(name)
        else:
            check.append(np.nan)
    else: #if search yielded no results
        track_ids.append(np.nan)
        artist_ids.append(np.nan)
        amt_features.append(np.nan)
        check.append(np.nan)
        low_pop.append(np.nan)
        remix.append(np.nan)

In [ ]:
def search2(dataframe):
    ids = []
    artist_ids = []
    check = [] #I will add all song titles to check as a sanity check
    amt_features = []
    for row in dataframe.iterrows():
        search = row[1][0].replace("\"", "") + " " + parse_artist(row[1][1])
        results = spotify.search(q=search,type='track', limit=1)
        res = results['tracks']['items']
        if len(res) == 0:
            ids.append(np.nan)
            check.append(np.nan)
            artist_ids.append(np.nan)
            amt_features.append(np.nan)
        else:
            ids.append(res[0]['id'])
            check.append(res[0]['name'])
            artist_ids.append(res[0]['artists'][0]['id'])
            amt_features.append(len(res[0]['artists']) - 1)
    dataframe['track_ids'] = ids
    dataframe['artist_ids'] = artist_ids       
    dataframe['check'] = check
    dataframe['amt_features'] = amt_features

While all of the artists and tracks are filled in, not all of them are accurate. Now we'll check the remixes, low popularity tracks, and those that otherwise need to be checked in a separate dataframe. While the performances are often the same, we are later going to extract features from each of the songs, so it is imperative that the ids are reflective of the original song, and not any alternative versions as that can immpact the analysis. For instance, one of the spotify features includes "instrumentalness". If that is in our data analysis it could artificially skew our data such that there may be higher instrumentalism than there actually is in music.

We check for whether the check column (which shows whether the search result name has any keys that may indicate an alternative form of the song) is not null, whether something is a remix and if so the name of the song, and if the song has a lower popularity.

Acousticness

  • A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic.

Danceability

  • Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.

Energy

  • Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy.

Instrumentalness

  • Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. "Ooh" and "aah" sounds are treated as instrumental in this context. Rap or spoken word tracks are clearly "vocal". The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. Values above 0.5 are intended to represent instrumental tracks, but confidence is higher as the value approaches 1.0.

Key

  • The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation. E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C/D, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1.

Liveness

  • Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live.

Loudness

  • The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Values typically range between -60 and 0 db. mode

Speechiness

  • Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks.

Valence

  • A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).

You can get more informtion regarding what each of these keys mean at https://developer.spotify.com/documentation/web-api/reference/#/operations/get-several-audio-features

I will split the trackids frame by groups of 100 within a larger list to limit the amount of API calls made, and get a dictionary of features for each track and add it on the list

In [ ]:
lst = list(frame['track_ids']) 
features = []
p = [lst[i:i + 100] for i in range(0, len(lst), 100)] #split the list by groups of 100 to address the limited API calls that can be made

for i in range(0,len(p)):
    features.append(spotify.audio_features(tracks=p[i])) 
    

features = list(np.concatenate(features).flat) #flatten list afterwards

We add the features to the dataframe

In [ ]:
frame["duration"] = list(map(lambda x: x['duration_ms'] , features))
frame["energy"] = list(map(lambda x: x['energy'] , features))

frame["loudness"] = list(map(lambda x: x['speechiness'] , features))

frame["tempo"] = list(map(lambda x: x['tempo'] , features))

Spotify doesn't have a genre attached to each song. To work around this, I will get the first genre attached to each artist.

In [ ]:
genres = []
for rows in frame.iterrows():
    if(type(rows[1][5]) == str):
        l = spotify.artist(artist_id=rows[1][5])
        if len(l['genres']) > 0:
            genres.append(l['genres'][0])
        else:
            genres.append(np.nan)
    else:
        genres.append(np.nan)

Several things remain consistent as time passed. For instance, danceability has always averaged at 0.64, suggesting to our hypothetical artist that a danceable song that people could move along to is an attribute in a popular song, and they should keep that in mind when making the song. Some notable trends include a small decrease in overall valence in songs, suggesting that musical positiveness conveyed by a track has taken a dip. In addition, "speechiness" has increased, suggesting that in the more popular songs today, there are more spoken words (rather than sung) which suggests an increased popularity in rap music, or rap music layered within sung words. This can also be seen with the noticable lack of instrumentalness, as values closer to 0 are more clearly "vocal". We can also see a large dip in the duration of songs, likely to increase the amount of streams one would get. Energy has also decreased, so on average, music isn't as fast, loud, and noisy as it was back in the late 2000s and early 2010s.

Suppose our hypothethical artist wants to have a song with high danceability, but wants to analyze how the tempo correlates with it. There appears to be a minimal negative correlation between tempo and danceability as seen in this graph with tempo vs. danceability, suggesting that there are other factors that may impact it but a really high tempo for a danceable track may not be the best idea, as most of the points within the top 20 are clustered at around the 120-140 tempo. It is also notable that the regression line for top 20 songs sits slightly higher than other songs, again suggesting to the artist that a danceable track may be a good idea.

Suggestions for the hypothetical artist:¶

A pop track with some hip hop elements, such as a feature from a hip hop or RnB artist. The song must be highly danceable with a tempo from 100-120 and not be very accoustic or low in valence.

Hypothesis: The largest indicator of the popularity of a song, based on the data collected, would have to be the genre and artist. If an artist themselves are popular, the songs that they put out are likely going to be popular too. In addition, the genre may be a great indicator. Dance Pop and Hip Hop are the most popular genres, so I believe that it would be most reflected in the data. I also think that the amt_feature could be a good determinator for whether the song would appear in the top 20, as a lot of songs, particularly nowadays, has a feature. I do not think the majority of the song features, such as duration, energy, and key would be great indicators as to whether or not a song is popular. The duration of a song, while it can artifically increase the amount of streams, doesn't determine the popularity of it. I think the features that could possibly have an impact are danceability and acousticness. I will use the Gini Model for splits

From Kaggle: The Gini index says, if we randomly select two items from a population, they must be of the same class and probability for this is 1 if the population is pure. It works with the categorical target variable Success or Failure. It performs only binary splits. The higher the value of Gini, higher the homogeneity. CART (Classification and Regression Tree) uses the Gini method to create binary splits.

In addition to prevent overfitting, I set the maximum depth of the tree as 3.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
clf_gini = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', max_depth=3, random_state=0)

# fit the model
clf_gini.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_gini = clf_gini.predict(X_test)

Insights and Conclusion:¶

At the root of the tree is X[1], which means that the artist is what determines the most upon whether a song is popular or not. The genre does not appear at the tree, which suggests that it is more closely tied to the artist due to the specific genre criteria, such as "canadian pop" ,"neo mellow", or "canadian hip hop" which is likely associated only with the artist Drake. One thing that is surprising is that the amt_features isn't a feature on the tree, as many artists are having more featured artists and collaborations in their tracks. Danceability is also a factor which was predicted, but key, tempo, and liveness are also factors that weren't predicted to be features in the tree. This could be a result of error, as live songs, for instance, can get into the data while searching, a sign of overfitting, or a legitimate factor. Maybe more artists are increasingly trying to get that live sound, like Ai Se Eu Te Pego, or a certain key that the track is in is preferred. Other factors, such as duration and valence aren't features in the tree.

The most important features, according to classification, is the artist making the track themselves, danceability, and tempo. These can be great insights for one trying to understand the general direction music is headed at. This does indicate what is popular, as a wide range of people listen to songs that make them happy and feel good, or feel better. It is also interesting to see how general observations that you kind of notice, such as the overall duration of songs being shorter, and songs being popular due to the fact that the artist themselves are popular, are supported by data. However these insights can be pretty limited as to what makes a song popular. There are many factors that go into the popularity of a song that go beyond the scope of simply the artist themselves, such as with production, songwriters, social influence, and the record label itself. Many songs can be popular because they aren't formulaic, and audiences appreciate that difference. Labels can also play a huge role into what makes music popular. Labels for instance pay radio stations and streamers to push out music, so that in itself is also a strategy that isn't present in the data. In addition, labels can purposefully push out a certain artist more than another. There are also some artists that are very popular within certain genres that isn't reflected on here and could be valuable in future analysis. There can also be limitations with the way that the data has been collected. While I am sure the majority of my data is correct, Spotify Search has the tendency of poducing bad results, so that can also be another factor to note. Finally, artists nowdays are quite versatile, and many expand further than just one genre. Since there was no genre attached to the track, I attached the first genre associated with the artist which isn't always reflective of the song, nor the artist themselves. While this is a great place to start, in the future what I can do to further expand on this data analysis is to include record labels, all writers, producers, and samples attached to the song, and have multiple genres attached to each song to better emphasize the fact that artists are more versatile and work with a wide range of genres. In addition what is existing in the data is one artist attached to each song. Obtaining all of the ArtistIDs can better indicate what songs are popular, as there are occasionally some cases where people listen to a song because of the featuring artist rather than the main artist. In addition, getting analytics of social media influence of artists, especially on TikTok which is changing the landscape of music, can be helpful to incorporate into the data as many popular songs that have made it to the list have been due to the sound going viral on TikTok. Regardless, this analysis provides some general insights into the direction music is headed in due to the frequency of certain genres, artists, and sound features.
